Pour 300ml cold salted @water{300%ml} into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting
lid. Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium and cover with the lid. Cook for
~{10%minutes} then remove from the heat. Keep covered for ~{10%minutes} or
until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Slice the @tomato{2} into thin wedges. Pick the @mint{5%g} leaves from their
stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Season the @Irish beef rump{250%g} with @BBQ Rub{1%sachet}, @salt{} and
@pepper{}. In a #small bowl{}, mix together the @yoghurt{75%g} and
@sriracha{1%sachet}. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Place a #large pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Once hot, fry the
beef until browned, ~{1-2%minutes} each side for medium-rare. Cook for another
~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you like it medium and a further
~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want it well-done.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging.
> Meat is safe to eat when outside is browned.

Once cooked, remove from the pan, cover and allow to rest.

In a #bowl{} for the salad, toss the tomato wedges together with the
@baby spinach{60%g} and a drizzle of @oil{}. Season to taste with salt and
pepper.

Mix the chopped mint through the rice.

Thinly slice the beef rump and divide between #plates{}. Serve the tomato
spinach salad, rice and sriracha yoghurt alongside.